  aggressiveDescription: Aggressive dogs display warning signs such as a stiff, forward-leaning
    posture, raised hackles, intense staring, bared teeth, and ears pinned back or
    rigidly forward. Do not attempt to pet or approach an aggressive dog. Remain
    calm, avoid direct eye contact, and slowly give the dog space. Sudden movements
    or attempts to touch the dog could provoke a bite.
  pleasedDescription: A happy dog typically has a loose, wiggly body, a sweeping
    tail wag, soft eyes, and an open, relaxed mouth that may look like a smile. This
    is usually a good time to interact. Approach calmly and allow the dog to come
    to you first. Gentle petting on the chest, shoulders, or side is generally well
    received.
  scaredDescription: A scared dog may crouch low, tuck its tail, flatten its ears,
    avoid eye contact, or tremble. Some frightened dogs may also yawn, lick their
    lips, or try to hide. Avoid petting or cornering a scared dog. Give it plenty
    of space, speak softly, and allow it to approach you when it feels safe and comfortable.
